    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-02-20T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-02-20T17:00:00-05:00" n="566"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d566">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1121 Smit, Albert H./8: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-02-20T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 20, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>71. Legation’s 137, February 18, 5 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Full instructions given in Department’s 63, February 17, 5 p.m.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Department concurs in view expressed in your paragraph 2, but queries the
                        point “demanding that the Chinese set aside the judgment”. Department hopes
                        that it will be possible for you to work the matter out with the Chinese
                        Government so that the action of the Chinese Magistrate will be ignored
                        without formal action in regard thereto.</item>
                    <pb facs="0611" n="513" xml:id="pg_513"/>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Department has discussed the matter with Chinese Minister here, and there
                        is concurrence in the hope that the matter will be settled after your
                        arrival in Nanking without leading to the creation of an issue.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
